name: The Vel Tones [US]
comments: Vocal and instrumental group active in the Southwest (California, Arizona, Nevada) in the late 1940s and early 1950s. Members include Rex Gallion, his brother, Von Gallion, Bob Moreau, Clyde Ridge and Eddie Robertson. The Gallion Brothers performed with Dude Martin in the early 1940s before they joined the armed services during World War II. While stationed in the Aleutian Islands, they met Bob Moreau and formed a five piece band, the "Aleutian Five." After their discharge from the army, the Aleutian Five moved to California and recorded for Decca. This group broke up when the Gallions and Moreau joined two other musicians to form the Vel-Tones with Moreau as the featured singer. By 1950 Moreau left the group and was replaced by Eddie Robertson. At the end of 1951 the group was a trio consisting of the Gallion Brothers and Clyde Ridge.

name: Toronto Mendelssohn Choir
comments: Large vocal ensemble.  It was co-founded in 1894 by Augustus S. Vogt and W. H. Hewlett to celebrate the opening of the Massey Hall.[2] The ensemble was originally an extension of the choir of Jarvis St. Baptist Church in Toronto which Vogt directed and Hewlett accompanied. It is named after the German composer, Felix Mendelssohn.  The choir has 150 voices, including a professional core of 20 singers along with auditioned amateur singers.  The choir performs secular and sacred choral masterpieces in its own annual concert series, as well as regular performances with the Toronto Symphony Orchestra

comments: Basic band moniker used by John Lennon and/or Yoko Ono to indicate their recording and/or performing with additional artists. Mainly used in the 1970s for joint recordings and releases in their respective own rights, but also for live appearances and one-off projects. Yoko Ono revived the name for her recordings in the 2000s. There are/were no constant members and none of the aliases indicates both main artists were actively involved in the respective other one's recordings/releases. The list of occasional participants includes a wide range of artists varying from Eric Clapton et al. via Free Jazz musicians to street music performers.
